{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric analysis (global P95/P05 computed over full series, then filtered to 2022-03-20 17:30–18:00 UTC+8), we observed many component-KPI pairs with a small number of anomalies (typically 2 highs and 2 lows) within the 30-minute window. The most extreme single KPI deviation was adservice-2 CPU (huge ratio to P95). Several other high-ratio anomalies (many network receive MB metrics and some container memory/CPU metrics) share earliest anomaly timestamps at or near 1647768600 and 1647768660, with other clusters at 1647768780, 1647768900, 1647769020, 1647769320, 1647769380, etc. error_logs.csv also shows heavy error rows concentrated on frontend-0/1/2 across the same time frame. To locate the root cause we need to see whether many metric anomalies are synchronized at the same timestamp(s) (indicating a system-wide event), and then correlate those timestamps with trace and log activity. The next step should therefore produce a compact per-timestamp aggregation of metric anomalies (within the incident window) so we can spot concentrated anomaly timestamps and affected components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv: 1) Recompute global P95 and P05 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full series (do not filter before computing). 2) Filter metric.csv to timestamps between 1647768600 and 1647770340 inclusive. 3) Mark a row as an anomaly if value > global_P95 or value < global_P05 for its (cmdb_id,kpi_name). 4) Aggregate anomalies by timestamp and produce a compact table of the top 20 timestamps sorted by anomaly count descending. For each timestamp row include: timestamp, anomaly_count, distinct_cmdb_count, earliest_dt_UTC+8 (for reference), and a sample list (up to 10 items) of affected (cmdb_id | kpi_name) pairs at that timestamp. Return only that compact table (limit 20 rows)." }

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global thresholds for metric KPIs (using full series) and identified concentrated anomaly minutes inside the incident window (2022-03-20 17:30–18:00 UTC+8). The top anomaly minutes are 1647770280 (17:58), 1647768660 (17:31), and 1647768600 (17:30). Many components are affected simultaneously (up to ~51 distinct cmdb_ids), and several high-severity anomalies are network receive metrics on containers hosted on node-5 (and some on node-6), plus an extreme CPU spike on adservice-2. error_logs.csv earlier showed the vast majority of error rows come from frontend-0/1/2. To localize the root cause we must correlate metric anomaly minutes to trace and log activity: specifically, find when frontend error messages surge (error_logs.csv) and whether trace anomalies point to a particular downstream faulty service/container (trace.csv). The next step should inspect error_logs.csv for temporal concentration of error messages within the incident window to determine the earliest error surge timestamp and which frontends are affected.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load error_logs.csv and filter to timestamps between 1647768600 and 1647770340 inclusive. Aggregate by timestamp and produce a compact table of up to top 20 timestamps sorted by row count descending. For each timestamp include: timestamp, row_count, distinct_cmdb_count, earliest_dt_UTC+8, and a sample list (up to 10) of cmdb_id with their row counts at that timestamp. Also return the overall counts per cmdb_id across the window (top 10 cmdb_id by total rows). Limit outputs to the described compact aggregates only."
}

